# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zsh-shell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The **Bourne shell** (**`sh`**) is a shell command-line interpreter for computer operating systems.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] It first appeared on Version 7 Unix, as its default shell.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Unix-like systems continue to have `/bin/sh`—which will be the Bourne shell, or a symbolic link or hard link to a compatible shell—even when other shells are used by most users.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The Bourne shell was once standard on all branded Unix systems, although historically BSD-based systems had many scripts written in csh.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] As the basis of POSIX `sh` syntax, Bourne shell scripts can typically be run with Bash or dash on Linux or other Unix-like systems; Bash itself is a free clone of Bourne.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Work on the Bourne shell initially started in 1976.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Developed by Stephen Bourne at Bell Labs, it was a replacement for the Thompson shell, whose executable file had the same name—`sh`.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The Bourne shell was also preceded by the Mashey shell.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Bourne was released in 1979 in the Version 7 Unix release distributed to colleges and universities.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] It gained popularity with the publication of *The Unix Programming Environment* by Brian Kernighan and Rob Pike—the first commercially published book that presented the shell as a programming language in a tutorial form.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The Bourne shell also was the first to feature the convention of using file descriptor `2>` for error messages, allowing much greater programmatic control during scripting by keeping error messages separate from data.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Stephen Bourne's coding style was influenced by his experience with the ALGOL 68C compiler that he had been working on at Cambridge University.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Moreover, – although the v7 shell is written in C – Bourne took advantage of some macros to give the C source code an ALGOL 68 flavor.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The resulting dialect of C has been nicknamed "Bournegol".
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] These macros (along with the finger command distributed in Unix version 4.2BSD) inspired the International Obfuscated C Code Contest (IOCCC).
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Over the years, the Bourne shell was enhanced at AT&T.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The various variants are thus called like the respective AT&T Unix version it was released with (some important variants being Version7, System III, SVR2, SVR3, SVR4).
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] As the shell was never versioned, the only way to identify it was testing its features.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Duplex Multi-Environment Real-Time (DMERT) is a hybrid time-sharing/real-time operating system developed in the 1970s at Bell Labs Indian Hill location in Naperville, Illinois uses a 1978 snapshot of Bourne Shell "VERSION sys137 DATE 1978 Oct 12 22:39:57".
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The DMERT shell runs on 3B21D computers still in use in the telecommunications industry.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The Korn shell (ksh) written by David Korn based on the original Bourne Shell source code, was a middle road between the Bourne shell and the C shell.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Its syntax was chiefly drawn from the Bourne shell, while its job control features resembled those of the C shell.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The functionality of the original Korn Shell (known as ksh88 from the year of its introduction) was used as a basis for the POSIX shell standard.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] A newer version, ksh93, has been open source since 2000 and is used on some Linux distributions.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] A clone of ksh88 known as pdksh is the default shell in OpenBSD.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Jörg Schilling's Schily-Tools includes three Bourne Shell derivatives.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Bill Joy, the author of the C shell, criticized the Bourne shell as being unfriendly for interactive use, a task for which Stephen Bourne himself acknowledged C shell's superiority.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Bourne stated, however, that his shell was superior for scripting and was available on any Unix system, and Tom Christiansen also criticized C shell as being unsuitable for scripting and programming.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] The Almquist Shell was ported to Linux, and the port renamed the Debian Almquist shell, or dash.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] This shell provides faster execution of standard `sh` (and POSIX-standard `sh`, in modern descendants) scripts with a smaller memory footprint than its counterpart, Bash.
[src:zsh-shell/bourne-shell] Its use tends to expose bashisms – bash-centric assumptions made in scripts meant to run on sh.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Command line interpreters are programs that allow a user to interact with the underlying operating system by typing commands at a command prompt using a command line interface (CLI), in contrast to pointing and clicking a mouse in a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Command-line completion allows the user to type the first few characters of a command, program, or filename, and press a completion key (normally Tab ↹) to fill in the rest of the item.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The user then presses Return or ↵ Enter to run the command or open the file.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Command-line completion is useful in several ways, as illustrated by the animation accompanying this article.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Commonly accessed commands, especially ones with long names, require fewer keystrokes to reach.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Commands with long or difficult to spell filenames can be entered by typing the first few characters and pressing a completion key, which completes the command or filename.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] In the case of multiple possible completions, some command-line interpreters, especially Unix shells, will list all possible completions beginning with those few characters.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The user can type more characters and press Tab ↹ again to see a new, narrowed-down list if the typed characters are still ambiguous, or else complete the command/filename with a trailing space.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] An alternate form of completion rotates through all matching results when the input is ambiguous.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Completable elements may include commands, arguments, file names and other entities, depending on the specific interpreter and its configuration.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Command-line completion generally only works in interactive mode.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] That is, it cannot be invoked to complete partially typed commands in scripts or batch files, even if the completion is unambiguous.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The name **tab completion** comes from the fact that command-line completion is often invoked by pressing the tab key.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Tab completion appeared early in computing history.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] One of the first examples was in the Berkeley Timesharing System for the SDS 940: if a typed string was unambiguous, the interpreter would automatically complete it without any user command.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] However, if the string was ambiguous, it did nothing.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] This feature was a mixed blessing, as it did not handle frequent typos well.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Later, developers of the TENEX operating system adopted the idea but made a crucial change.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] They introduced "escape recognition," where autocompletion occurred only when the user pressed the Escape key (hence the name).
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] TENEX also expanded autocompletion from just program names (as in the Berkeley system) to both program names and filenames.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The TENEX descendant TOPS-20 moved command line completion from the command interpreter to the operating system via the COMND JSYS system call, making it available to other user applications.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Separately, the CAB 500 computer (1960) featured a programming language with French keyword autocompletion called PAF.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Instead we can use command-line completion.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The following example shows how command-line completion works in Bash.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] Other command line shells may perform slightly differently.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] But this time introduction-to-command-line-completion.html is not the only file in the current directory that starts with "i".
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The directory also contains files introduction-to-bash.html and introduction-to-firefox.html.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] This is just eight keystrokes, which is considerably less than 52 keystrokes we would have needed to type without using command-line completion.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] The following example shows how command-line completion works with rotating completion, such as Windows's CMD uses.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] This is just seven keystrokes, comparable to prompting-style completion.
[src:zsh-shell/tab-completion] This works best if we know what possibilities the interpreter will rotate through.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] A **Unix shell** is a shell that provides a command-line user interface for a Unix-like operating system.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] A Unix shell provides a command language that can be used either interactively or for writing a shell script.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] A user typically works within a Unix shell via a terminal emulator; however, direct access via serial hardware connections or a Secure Shell are common for server systems.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Although use of a Unix shell is popular with some users, others prefer to use a graphical shell in a windowing system, such as those provided in desktop Linux distributions or macOS, instead of a command-line interface (CLI).
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] A user may have access to multiple Unix shells with one configured to run by default when the user logs in interactively.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The default selection is typically stored in a user's profile (for example, in the local passwd file or in a distributed configuration system such as NIS or LDAP).
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] A user may use other shells nested inside the default shell.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] A Unix shell may provide many features including: variable definition and substitution, command substitution, filename wildcarding, stream piping, control flow structures (condition-testing and iteration), working directory context, and here document.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The first Unix shell was the Thompson shell, *sh*, written by Ken Thompson at Bell Labs and distributed with Versions 1 through 6 of Unix, from 1971 to 1975.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Though rudimentary by modern standards, it introduced many of the basic features common to all later Unix shells, including piping, simple control structures using `if` and `goto`, and filename GLOBbing.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Though not in current use, it is still available as part of some Ancient UNIX systems, such as Version 6 Unix.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] It was modeled after the Multics shell, developed in 1965 by American software engineer Glenda Schroeder.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Schroeder's Multics shell was itself modeled after the RUNCOM program Louis Pouzin showed to the Multics Team.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The "rc" suffix on some Unix configuration files (e.g.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] ".bashrc" or ".vimrc"), is a remnant of the RUNCOM ancestry of Unix shells.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The PWB shell or Mashey shell, *sh*, was an upward-compatible version of the Thompson shell, augmented by John Mashey and others and distributed with the Programmer's Workbench UNIX, circa 1975–1977.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] It focused on making shell programming practical, especially in large shared computing centers.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] It added shell variables (precursors of environment variables, including the search path mechanism that evolved into $PATH), user-executable shell scripts, and interrupt-handling.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Control structures were extended from if/goto to if/then/else/endif, switch/breaksw/endsw, and while/end/break/continue.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] As shell programming became widespread, these external commands were incorporated into the shell itself for performance.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] But the most widely distributed and influential of the early Unix shells were the Bourne shell and the C shell.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Both shells have been used as the coding base and model for many derivative and work-alike shells with extended feature sets.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The Bourne shell, *sh*, was a new Unix shell by Stephen Bourne at Bell Labs.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Distributed as the shell for UNIX Version 7 in 1979, it introduced the rest of the basic features considered common to all the later Unix shells, including here documents, command substitution, more generic variables and more extensive builtin control structures.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The language, including the use of a reversed keyword to mark the end of a block, was influenced by ALGOL 68.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Traditionally, the Bourne shell program name is sh and its path in the Unix file system hierarchy is /bin/sh.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] But a number of compatible work-alikes are also available with various improvements and additional features.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The POSIX standard specifies its standard shell as a strict subset of the Korn shell.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] From a user's perspective the Bourne shell was immediately recognized when active by its characteristic default command line prompt character, the dollar sign ($).
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The C shell, *csh*, was modeled on the C programming language, including the control structures and the expression grammar.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] It was written by Bill Joy as a graduate student at University of California, Berkeley, and was widely distributed with BSD Unix.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The C shell also introduced many features for interactive work, including the history and editing mechanisms, aliases, directory stacks, tilde notation, cdpath, job control and path hashing.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] On many systems, csh may be a symbolic link or hard link to TENEX C shell (tcsh), an improved version of Joy's original version.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Although the interactive features of csh have been copied to most other shells, the language structure has not been widely copied.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The only work-alike is Hamilton C shell, written by Nicole Hamilton, first distributed on OS/2 in 1988 and on Windows since 1992.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Shells read configuration files in various circumstances.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] These files usually contain commands for the shell and are executed when loaded; they are usually used to set important variables used to find executables, like $PATH, and others that control the behavior and appearance of the shell.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] The table in this section shows the configuration files for popular shells.
[src:zsh-shell/unix-shell] Same behavior as sh, but only if invoked as sh (bash 2+) or, since bash 4.2, also if invoked *explicitly* in POSIX compatibility mode (with options --posix or -o posix).
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] The **Z shell** (**Zsh**) is a shell and a command-line interpreter for shell scripts.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Zsh was created by Paul Falstad in 1990 while he was a student at Princeton University.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] It combines features from both ksh and tcsh (and rc to a lesser extent), offering functionality such as programmable command-line completion, extended file globbing, improved variable/array handling, and themeable prompts.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Zsh is available for most POSIX / Unix-like operating systems as well as Microsoft Windows as part of Cygwin or the UnxUtils collection and has been adopted as the default interactive shell for macOS, Deepin, TrueNAS and Kali Linux.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] The "Oh My Zsh" user community website provides a platform for third-party plug-ins and themes, featuring a large and active contributor base.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Paul Falstad wrote the first version of Zsh in 1990 while a student at Princeton University.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] The name *Zsh* derives from the name of Zhong Shao, a teaching assistant at Princeton University.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Falstad regarded Shao's login, "zsh", as a good name for a shell.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Zsh was at first intended to be a subset of csh for the Amiga, but expanded far beyond that.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Ports of Zsh for Microsoft Windows have been available via Cygwin at least since around 1997, and Zsh is supplied as an official Cygwin package since 2002.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] It is also available as part of the UnxUtils collection of native Win32 ports of common GNU Unix-like utilities (though Zsh, unlike Bash, is not part of the GNU project itself).
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] In 2019, macOS Catalina adopted Zsh as the default login shell, replacing the GPLv2 licensed version of Bash, and when Bash is run interactively on Catalina, a warning is shown by default.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] The default shell of TrueNAS (formerly FreeNAS) changed from csh to Zsh in FreeNAS 11.2 released in late 2018.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] In 2020, Kali Linux adopted Zsh as the default shell since its 2020.4 release.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] A user community website known as "Oh My Zsh" collects third-party plug-ins and themes for the Z shell.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] As of 2024, their GitHub repository has over 2300 contributors, over 300 plug-ins, and over 140 themes.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] It also comes with an auto-update tool that makes it easier to keep installed plug-ins and themes updated.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] Beyond integrated frameworks, the independent community repository zsh-users on GitHub hosts several widely-used standalone extensions.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] These include zsh-completions for advanced command tab-completion definitions, zsh-syntax-highlighting for real-time command-line highlighting, and zsh-autosuggestions for history-based command recommendations.
[src:zsh-shell/z-shell] The same organization also developed Antigen, one of the earliest popular plugin managers for Zsh.
